ration is a critical site of political conflict, and the ways it has changed over the years reflect the ongoing competition over what it has meant to be Japanese American. Kurashige reveals, subtly and with attention to gender issues, the tensions that emerged at different moments, not only between those who emphasized Japanese ethnicity and those who stressed American orientation, but also between generations and classes in this complex community.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aCitizens' associationsxHistoryx20th centuryxCaliforniaxLos Angeles. 0aCitizens' associationszCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistoryy20th century. 0aEthnic festivalsxHistoryx20th centuryxCaliforniaxLos Angeles. 0aEthnic festivalszCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistoryy20th century. 0aJapanese AmericansxEthnic identityxCaliforniaxLos Angeles. 0aJapanese AmericansxSocial conditionsx20th centuryxCaliforniaxLos Angeles. 0aJapanese AmericansxSocial life and customsx20th centuryxCaliforniaxLos Angeles. 0aJapanese AmericanszCaliforniazLos AngelesxEthnic identity. 0aJapanese AmericanszCaliforniazLos AngelesxSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aJapanese AmericanszCaliforniazLos AngelesxSocial life and customsy20th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520926479423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520926479.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles